window.TOPICS_EN={"wegebau": {"id": "wegebau", "title": "Path Construction – Layer Structure & Paving", "intro": "In path construction, paths and surfaces are built up from several coordinated layers that distribute the loads from top to bottom and make the surface frost-resistant and load-bearing. This module explains the layer structure, the appropriate materials and grain sizes, as well as the installation of edge restraints and the most important paving and slab bonds.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "The big picture: why paths are built in layers", "html": "<p>A path is not a single slab but a <b>system of several layers</b>. From above come loads (feet, bicycles, a car); below there is often soft ground with a low bearing capacity. Each layer <b>distributes the load over a larger area</b> and passes it on, weakened, to the next layer, until the subgrade / natural ground can take it up without damage.</p><p>Three basic rules govern the structure:</p><ul><li><b>Distribute loads:</b> towards the bottom the grain sizes become coarser and the layers more load-bearing.</li><li><b>Drain water:</b> all layers are as water-permeable as possible, and there is a cross slope / gradient of about 2.5 %.</li><li><b>Ward off frost:</b> only frost-resistant materials, so that the ground does not heave in winter (frost heave).</li></ul><p>Every installed layer is compacted so that it does not settle later.</p>"}, {"heading": "The standard layer structure (from top to bottom)", "html": "<p>This is what the standard layer structure of a path typically looks like. In practice, the frost-protection layer and the base course are often combined into a single frost-protection / base course mixture.</p><table><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Function</th><th>Material (example)</th><th>Thickness</th></tr><tr><td><b>Surface course / wearing surface</b></td><td>walkable/driveable surface, wear, appearance, cross slope</td><td>concrete pavers, clinker, natural stone, slabs or a water-bound surface</td><td>stone thickness 4–8 cm</td></tr><tr><td><b>chippings bedding 2/5</b></td><td>even support, height compensation, drainage</td><td>chippings 2/5 (or crushed sand)</td><td>3–5 cm</td></tr><tr><td><b>crushed-stone base course 0/32</b></td><td>carries the loads and distributes them</td><td>crushed stone / mineral mixture 0/32 (or 0/45)</td><td>15–30 cm</td></tr><tr><td><b>frost-protection layer</b></td><td>prevents frost damage, drains water away</td><td>frost-resistant gravel/sand 0/32 or 0/45</td><td>15–40 cm</td></tr><tr><td><b>formation level</b></td><td>profiled, compacted surface with a cross slope – the boundary with the superstructure</td><td>(worked subgrade)</td><td>—</td></tr><tr><td><b>Subgrade / substructure</b></td><td>bears the entire structure</td><td>natural ground or fill / embankment</td><td>—</td></tr></table><p>The thickness of the frost-protection layer and base course depends on the load and the frost zone: a car driveway needs considerably more than a garden path.</p>"}, {"heading": "The three zones: superstructure, substructure and subgrade", "html": "<p>The entire structure is divided into three zones. The decisive dividing line is the <b>formation level</b>.</p><ul><li><b>subgrade / natural ground:</b> the naturally occurring, native / undisturbed soil. It is not built but is already there.</li><li><b>substructure:</b> an artificially created zone between the subgrade and the formation level – e.g. an embankment / dam of fill if the path is to sit higher, or a soil replacement. It is not always necessary.</li><li><b>superstructure / pavement structure:</b> all the load-bearing layers <b>above the formation level</b> – frost-protection layer, crushed-stone base course, bedding and surface course.</li></ul><p>Rule of thumb: everything <b>above</b> the formation level is superstructure, everything <b>below</b> the formation level is substructure or subgrade. The formation level itself must be properly compacted, have the intended cross slope and provide sufficient bearing capacity.</p>"}, {"heading": "Reading grain sizes: 0/4, 0/32 and 2/5", "html": "<p>Grain gradings are given with two numbers, d/D. The <b>first number</b> is the smallest grain (smallest grain size), the <b>second number</b> the largest grain (largest grain size).</p><ul><li><b>0/4</b> = a grain mixture with all grains from 0 to 4 mm. The 0 means that fine material / fines are included (sand, filler). Such 0/x mixtures compact well and are used for base and frost-protection layers.</li><li><b>0/32</b> = a crushed-stone / mineral mixture from 0 to 32 mm for the load-bearing crushed-stone base course.</li><li><b>2/5</b> = chippings without fines, only grains from 2 to 5 mm. It has many voids, lets water through and serves as bedding under pavers and slabs.</li></ul><p>Rule of thumb: if the designation starts with <b>0</b>, fines are included (compacts well, load-bearing). If it starts with a number greater than 0, it is pure chippings (water-permeable, for the bedding).</p>"}, {"heading": "Edge restraints: kerb stone, concrete bedding and back support", "html": "<p>Edge restraints (e.g. kerb stones, kerbs, lawn edgings) bound the surface. Their tasks:</p><ul><li>give the paved surface <b>lateral support</b> (abutment) so that it does not spread apart;</li><li>absorb horizontal / thrust forces that arise when driving over it or braking;</li><li>create a <b>clean, clear boundary</b> between the path and the adjacent area (lawn, bed);</li><li>establish height differences (e.g. between the carriageway and the footpath) and prevent bedding and jointing material from being washed out.</li></ul><p>A kerb stone is usually set in concrete:</p><ul><li><b>concrete bedding / footing:</b> the stone stands on an earth-moist concrete foundation that gives it firm, even support.</li><li><b>back support / haunching:</b> a wedge-shaped concrete fillet at the <b>back</b> of the stone. It supports it against tipping and against lateral pressure. The back support only reaches about two-thirds of the stone height and stays below the top edge, so that it is later concealed by soil or grass.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Installing kerb stones in concrete – workflow", "html": "<p>Example: 40 m of kerb stones for a car driveway, from delivery to invoice. A sensible sequence:</p><ul><li><b>1. Prepare:</b> receive and check the material (kerb stones, concrete/cement, chippings), set up the site and secure it.</li><li><b>2. Survey:</b> set up the string line / batter boards, establish the alignment, height and cross slope and tension the string.</li><li><b>3. Excavate the trench:</b> dig the foundation trench to the correct width and depth.</li><li><b>4. Formation level:</b> level off the trench bottom and compact it.</li><li><b>5. Place the concrete bedding:</b> install earth-moist concrete as the foundation.</li><li><b>6. Set the stones:</b> set the kerb stones to the string in alignment and height, adjust them with the rubber mallet, keep the joints even.</li><li><b>7. Back support:</b> form the concrete against the back.</li><li><b>8. Curing & joints:</b> let the concrete cure, fill the joints if necessary.</li><li><b>9. Clean up:</b> clean the site, dispose of leftover material.</li><li><b>10. Billing:</b> take the measurement / take-off (billing by linear metres) and issue the invoice.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Pavers & slabs: clinker, bonds and joints", "html": "<p>A <b>clinker brick</b> is a brick made of clay that is fired until it sinters at such a high temperature that it becomes dense. This makes it very hard, frost-resistant, abrasion-resistant and it absorbs hardly any water. It is used as a paving clinker and as a facing brick.</p><p>The appearance and the load-bearing capacity depend on the laying pattern / bond. Important: a good interlock prevents continuous joints and distributes the load.</p><p><b>Concrete pavers – typical laying methods:</b></p><ul><li><b>herringbone bond:</b> stones in a 45° or 90° zigzag; very high interlock, ideal for driveways and heavily trafficked surfaces.</li><li><b>stretcher / running bond:</b> rows, each offset by half a stone length – as in masonry.</li><li><b>elbow bond:</b> an interlocking pattern for interlocking pavers that form an L-shape.</li></ul><p><b>Slabs – typical laying methods:</b></p><ul><li><b>row / linear bond:</b> straight rows with continuous joints in one direction.</li><li><b>cross-joint bond:</b> the joints run through in both directions (cross joints), and four slabs meet at one point. Rather unsuitable for loaded paved surfaces because of the lack of interlock, but a common pattern for slabs.</li><li><b>diagonal bond:</b> rows rotated by 45° (also possible as a random / Roman bond with various formats).</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Key technical terms in brief", "html": "<ul><li><b>formation level:</b> the profiled, compacted surface of the subgrade/substructure with a cross slope – the boundary with the superstructure.</li><li><b>compacting:</b> pressing the layers together with a plate compactor or roller so that the surface becomes load-bearing and settlement-proof; always layer by layer.</li><li><b>water-bound surface:</b> a surface course made of a mineral mixture (e.g. 0/8 or 0/16) that is bound only by fines and water – without cement or bitumen. Natural appearance, water-permeable, typical for park and garden paths, but it must be maintained.</li><li><b>Frost-protection layer:</b> the bottom layer of the superstructure made of frost-resistant gravel/sand; prevents frost heave and drains water away.</li><li><b>Crushed-stone base course 0/32:</b> the load-bearing layer of crushed stone 0–32 mm, distributes the loads.</li><li><b>Chippings bedding 2/5:</b> 3–5 cm of chippings as support for pavers and slabs.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Hand tools for paving", "html": "<p>The path-construction module explains layers, grain sizes and bonds – here are the <b>hand tools</b> with which this is actually done on the building site. The tool boxes from the equipment shed mainly contain maintenance and planting tools; the paving tools have been missing entirely so far.</p><table><tr><th>Tool</th><th>English</th><th>Use</th></tr><tr><td><b>Wasserwaage</b></td><td>spirit level</td><td>Check the gradient and evenness (water must run away from the house)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Setzlatte / Richtlatte</b></td><td>screed board / straightedge</td><td>Screed off the chippings bedding and check the finished surface for evenness</td></tr><tr><td><b>Richtschnur und Pflöcke</b></td><td>string line and pegs</td><td>Mark out lines, edges and heights – the basis for every straight row</td></tr><tr><td><b>Gummihammer</b></td><td>rubber mallet</td><td>Tap pavers and slabs into place without damaging them</td></tr><tr><td><b>Pflasterhammer</b></td><td>paving hammer</td><td>Set, drive and trim stones</td></tr><tr><td><b>Fäustel</b></td><td>club hammer / lump hammer</td><td>Striking, chiselling, driving in pegs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Vorschlaghammer</b></td><td>sledgehammer</td><td>Heavy blows, demolition work</td></tr><tr><td><b>Fugeneisen / Fugenkelle</b></td><td>jointing iron</td><td>Draw and fill joints</td></tr><tr><td><b>Fugenkratzer</b></td><td>joint scraper</td><td>Scrape out old joints and joint weeds</td></tr><tr><td><b>Maurerkelle</b></td><td>trowel</td><td>Apply mortar and concrete (concrete bedding, back support)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Handramme / Handstampfer</b></td><td>hand tamper</td><td>Compact small areas and corners where the plate compactor cannot reach</td></tr><tr><td><b>Zollstock / Gliedermaßstab</b></td><td>folding rule</td><td>Short measurements, measuring layer thicknesses</td></tr><tr><td><b>Maßband / Rollmeter</b></td><td>tape measure</td><td>Measure longer distances, set out the area</td></tr></table><p><b>Remember:</b> string line → height and alignment, screed board → evenness, spirit level → cross slope, rubber mallet → tap the stone to height. This is the order in which you work when paving.</p>"}, {"heading": "Building materials", "html": "<p>Chippings, crushed stone, crushed sand, pavers/clinker and kerb stones are explained in the path-construction module; grass seed, turf, fertiliser and compost in the lawn module. These four materials have been missing so far:</p><table><tr><th>Material</th><th>English</th><th>Use</th></tr><tr><td><b>Pflanzerde / Substrat</b></td><td>planting soil / substrate</td><td>Planting and soil improvement; filled into the planting hole so that the roots establish well</td></tr><tr><td><b>Rindenmulch</b></td><td>bark mulch</td><td>Covering beds: slows weeds, keeps moisture in the soil and protects against silting/capping. Layer thickness approx. 5–7 cm; binds nitrogen as it rots, so fertilise beforehand</td></tr><tr><td><b>Unkrautvlies</b></td><td>weed control fabric / geotextile</td><td>Under gravel areas and paths; separates the layers and holds back weeds, but is water-permeable</td></tr><tr><td><b>Pflanzpfahl und Anbindematerial</b></td><td>tree stake and tie</td><td>Stabilise young trees so that the root ball does not wobble in the wind. The tie is made in the shape of a <b>figure eight</b> (loose, so that the trunk does not grow into it)</td></tr></table>"}], "exam": [{"q": "Sketch or describe the standard layer structure of a path (from top to bottom).", "answer": "From top to bottom: <b>surface course/wearing surface</b> (pavers, slabs or a water-bound surface) → <b>chippings bedding 2/5</b> (3–5 cm) → <b>crushed-stone base course 0/32</b> (approx. 15–30 cm) → <b>frost-protection layer</b> (frost-resistant gravel/sand, approx. 15–40 cm) → <b>formation level</b> (profiled, compacted boundary with the superstructure) → <b>subgrade or substructure</b>. The frost-protection layer and base course can be combined into a single frost-protection / base course mixture. All layers are compacted, and the surface is given a cross slope of about 2.5 %.", "hints": ["A path consists of several layers that distribute the load downwards – think from the walkable surface down to the ground.", "Above the natural ground lies first the formation level, above that the frost-resistant and load-distributing layers, and at the very top the bedding and surfacing.", "Order from the top: surfacing → bedding (chippings 2/5) → crushed-stone base course (0/32) → frost-protection layer → formation level → subgrade."]}, {"q": "Name the individual layers with their function and one suitable material each.", "answer": "<b>Surface course/wearing surface:</b> walkable/driveable surface, wear and appearance – e.g. concrete pavers, clinker, natural stone, slabs or a water-bound surface. <b>Chippings bedding 2/5:</b> even support and height compensation, drains – chippings 2/5. <b>Crushed-stone base course 0/32:</b> carries and distributes the loads – crushed stone / mineral mixture 0/32 (or 0/45). <b>Frost-protection layer:</b> prevents frost damage and drains water away – frost-resistant gravel/sand 0/32 or 0/45. <b>Formation level/subgrade:</b> bears the entire structure – natural ground or fill.", "hints": ["Go through each layer and ask: what is it for and what is it made of?", "Match them up: frost protection = frost/water, base course = carrying loads, bedding = support, surface course = surface.", "Examples: frost-protection layer of frost-resistant gravel 0/45, crushed-stone base course of 0/32, chippings bedding of 2/5, surface course of concrete pavers."]}, {"q": "What does the grain size 0/4 mean?", "answer": "0/4 denotes a grain mixture with grains from 0 to 4 mm. The first number is the smallest grain (smallest grain size), the second the largest grain (largest grain size). The 0 means that fine material (sand, filler) is included – such 0/x mixtures compact well and are used for base and frost-protection layers.", "hints": ["The two numbers denote a range of grain sizes.", "The first number is the smallest grain, the second the largest.", "0 means: fines from 0 mm are included, the largest grain is 4 mm – so a mixture from 0 to 4 mm."]}, {"q": "Explain the difference between superstructure, substructure and subgrade.", "answer": "<b>Subgrade:</b> the naturally occurring, native soil – it is already there and is not built. <b>Substructure:</b> an artificially created zone between the subgrade and the formation level, e.g. a fill/embankment to raise the path, or a soil replacement. <b>Superstructure:</b> all the load-bearing layers <b>above the formation level</b> (frost-protection layer, crushed-stone base course, bedding, surface course). The dividing line between below and above is the formation level.", "hints": ["Think of three zones: what is naturally there, what is filled up, and what carries the traffic.", "The boundary between 'below' and 'above' is the formation level.", "Subgrade = natural ground; substructure = artificial fill/embankment up to the formation level; superstructure = all layers above the formation level."]}, {"q": "What tasks do edge restraints have?", "answer": "Edge restraints give the paved surface <b>lateral support</b> (an abutment) so that it does not spread apart, absorb <b>horizontal forces</b> (e.g. when braking), create a <b>clean boundary</b> between the path and the adjacent area, establish <b>height differences</b> and prevent bedding and jointing material from being washed out. They also protect the edges of the surfacing.", "hints": ["Consider what happens to paving if it has no lateral support.", "It is about lateral forces and bounding the surface.", "Name: lateral support/abutment against shifting, absorption of horizontal forces, clean boundary, height separation and protection of the edges."]}, {"q": "Explain the concrete bedding and back support of a kerb stone.", "answer": "<b>Concrete bedding:</b> the kerb stone stands on an earth-moist concrete foundation that gives it firm, even support (the bed on which it sits). <b>Back support:</b> a wedge-shaped concrete fillet at the back of the stone that supports it against tipping and lateral pressure. It only reaches about two-thirds of the stone height and stays below the top edge, so that it is later concealed by soil or grass.", "hints": ["A kerb stone needs a firm foundation and support against tipping.", "Concrete bedding = what the stone stands on; back support = what holds it from behind.", "Concrete bedding: earth-moist concrete foundation under the stone. Back support: a concrete wedge at the back, max. ~2/3 of the stone height, below the top edge, against tipping/horizontal forces."]}, {"q": "Describe the work steps for installing 40 m of kerb stones in concrete for a car driveway – from material delivery to billing.", "answer": "1. Receive and check the material, set up and secure the site. 2. Set up the string line/batter boards and establish the alignment, height and cross slope (tension the string). 3. Excavate the foundation trench to the correct width/depth. 4. Level off the trench bottom as the formation level and compact it. 5. Place earth-moist concrete as the concrete bedding. 6. Set the kerb stones to the string in alignment and height, adjust them with the rubber mallet, even joints. 7. Form the back support from concrete. 8. Let the concrete cure, fill the joints if necessary. 9. Clean the site, dispose of leftover material. 10. Take the measurement (by linear metres) and issue the invoice.", "hints": ["Start with the delivery/site setup and end with the measurement and invoice.", "In between: survey (string/alignment/height), excavate the trench, formation level, concrete, set the stones, back support, curing, cleaning.", "Order: check/secure material → string line/batter boards → trench → compact the formation level → concrete bedding → set the stones → back support → curing/joints → clean → measurement (linear metres) and billing."]}, {"q": "What is a clinker (brick)?", "answer": "A clinker is a building block made of clay that is fired at a very high temperature until it sinters (sintering / vitrification), so that the material becomes dense. This makes it very hard, frost-resistant and abrasion-resistant, and it absorbs hardly any water. It is used as a paving clinker (surfacing) and as a facing brick (cladding). The high firing distinguishes it from an ordinary brick.", "hints": ["It is a building block made of clay – but with a special feature in the firing.", "It is fired so hot that the material becomes dense (sinters).", "Clinker = a brick fired until it sinters: dense, hard, frost-resistant, low water absorption; as a paving and facing clinker."]}, {"q": "Name 3 types of concrete-paver laying.", "answer": "Three typical laying methods are the <b>stretcher/running bond</b> (offset rows as in masonry), the <b>herringbone bond</b> (45° or 90° zigzag, very high interlock, ideal for driveways) and the <b>elbow bond</b> (an interlocking pattern for interlocking pavers). Further options are the row bond or the random bond.", "hints": ["Think of laying patterns (bonds); the interlock is important for the load-bearing capacity.", "For driveways, strongly interlocking patterns are well suited.", "For example: stretcher/running bond, herringbone bond, elbow bond."]}, {"q": "Name 3 types of slab laying.", "answer": "Three typical laying methods are the <b>row/linear bond</b> (straight rows, continuous joints in one direction), the <b>cross-joint bond</b> (joints run through in both directions, cross joints) and the <b>diagonal bond</b> (rows rotated by 45°). The random or Roman bond with various formats is also possible.", "hints": ["Slabs are usually laid in even patterns.", "The joints can run in rows, in a cross or diagonally.", "For example: row/linear bond, cross-joint bond, diagonal bond (or random/Roman bond)."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term frost-protection layer.", "answer": "The frost-protection layer is the bottom layer of the superstructure (directly above the formation level). It consists of frost-resistant, water-permeable material (e.g. gravel/sand 0/32 or 0/45). Its task: it prevents frost damage and frost heave because it has hardly any frost-susceptible fines and drains water away quickly.", "hints": ["The name reveals the task – it is about winter.", "It lies at the very bottom of the superstructure and must drain water away.", "Frost-resistant gravel/sand (0/32 or 0/45) that prevents frost heave and drains."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term crushed-stone base course 0/32.", "answer": "The crushed-stone base course is the load-bearing layer of the superstructure, made of crushed stone / mineral mixture with a grain size of 0 to 32 mm. It takes up the loads from above and distributes them over a larger area below. It is installed and compacted layer by layer.", "hints": ["The name says what the layer does: it 'carries'.", "0/32 describes the grain size: 0 to 32 mm with fines, compacts well.", "A load-bearing crushed-stone layer 0–32 mm that takes up loads and distributes them downwards."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term chippings bedding 2/5.", "answer": "The chippings bedding is a roughly 3–5 cm thick layer of chippings with a grain size of 2 to 5 mm (without fines). Pavers or slabs are laid on it. It creates an even support, allows a small height compensation and lets water through.", "hints": ["It lies directly beneath the surfacing.", "2/5 is pure chippings without fines, water-permeable.", "3–5 cm of chippings 2/5 as even support for pavers/slabs."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term water-bound surface.", "answer": "A water-bound surface is a surface course made of a graded mineral mixture (e.g. 0/8 or 0/16) that is bound only by its fines and water – without cement or bitumen. It is compacted, looks natural, is water-permeable and is often used for park and garden paths; however, it must be maintained.", "hints": ["The name reveals the binder.", "It is a surface course without cement/bitumen, typical for park paths.", "A compacted mineral mixture bound only by fines and water – a natural, water-permeable surface."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term compacting.", "answer": "Compacting means pressing a layer together with a plate compactor or a roller so that the voids are reduced. This increases the density, load-bearing capacity and stability and avoids later settlement. Compacting is always done layer by layer, i.e. layer upon layer.", "hints": ["It is about making the material firmer and denser.", "Which machines are used for it, and why is it important?", "Press together with a plate compactor/roller, layer by layer – increases load-bearing capacity and prevents settlement."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term formation level.", "answer": "The formation level is the profiled, compacted surface of the subgrade or substructure on which the superstructure is built. It has the intended cross slope and forms the boundary between the substructure/subgrade (below) and the superstructure (above). It must be sufficiently load-bearing and even.", "hints": ["It is an important dividing line in the structure.", "The superstructure and substructure are separated by it.", "A profiled, compacted surface with a cross slope – the boundary between the substructure/subgrade and the superstructure."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term herringbone bond.", "answer": "In the herringbone bond, the stones are laid at a 45° or 90° angle in a zigzag pattern that resembles a fish bone. It has a very high interlock, distributes loads well and hardly shifts – which is why it is particularly suitable for driveways and heavily trafficked surfaces.", "hints": ["The name describes the pattern.", "The stones lie diagonally in a zigzag (45° or 90°).", "A zigzag pattern with high interlock, ideal for heavily loaded surfaces such as driveways."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term stretcher/running bond.", "answer": "In the stretcher/running bond, the stones are laid in straight rows, with each row offset by half a stone length – similar to masonry. This means there are no continuous cross joints, and a simple, even pattern results.", "hints": ["Think of the pattern of a brick wall.", "The rows are offset against each other.", "Rows, each offset by half a stone length – as in masonry."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term elbow bond.", "answer": "The elbow bond is a laying pattern for interlocking pavers that form an angled L- or elbow shape. The stones interlock (interlocking bond) and produce a stable pattern with good load-bearing capacity.", "hints": ["The name describes the shape of the stones.", "It is about interlocking pavers that mesh together.", "An interlocking pattern of L-/elbow-shaped interlocking pavers with good interlock."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term row/linear bond.", "answer": "In the row/linear bond, the stones or slabs are laid in straight rows so that the joints run through in one direction (the rows are flush). It is a simple, calm pattern that is used especially for slabs.", "hints": ["The name describes the arrangement.", "The joints run straight through in one direction.", "Straight rows with continuous joints in one direction, often for slabs."]}, {"q": "Explain the technical term cross joints.", "answer": "Cross joints are joints that run through in both directions so that four stones or slabs meet at one point and form a cross. On loaded paved surfaces, cross joints are unfavourable because the interlock is missing and the load is poorly distributed; on slab surfaces, however, they are common as an even grid pattern (cross-joint bond).", "hints": ["The name describes how the joints meet.", "Four stones/slabs meet at one point.", "Continuous joints in both directions (a cross) – unfavourable on load-bearing surfaces because of the lack of interlock, but usual for slabs."]}]}, "rasen": {"id": "rasen", "title": "Lawns – Establishment & Care", "intro": "A lawn is a dense, close-growing area of grasses that fulfils many functions in horticulture and landscaping – from sports and play areas to ornamental greenery and erosion protection. Anyone who establishes and maintains a lawn correctly ensures a dense, hard-wearing and permanently green sward.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "What is a lawn? The four types of lawn", "html": "<p>A lawn is a dense, closed area of lawn grasses kept short by regular mowing. Depending on use and wear tolerance, four types are distinguished:</p><table><tr><th>Type of lawn</th><th>Use</th><th>Wear tolerance / characteristics</th></tr><tr><td><b>Ornamental lawn</b></td><td>Front gardens, ornamental areas</td><td>low wear tolerance, fine-leaved, very dense, high maintenance</td></tr><tr><td><b>General-purpose lawn</b></td><td>Home gardens, parks, public green spaces</td><td>medium wear tolerance, robust, low-maintenance (all-rounder)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Hard-wearing / sports lawn</b></td><td>Sports, play and lounging areas</td><td>high wear tolerance, tread-resistant, very quick to regenerate</td></tr><tr><td><b>Landscape lawn</b></td><td>Embankments, roadside greenery, near-natural areas</td><td>low wear tolerance, extensive/low-maintenance, provides erosion protection</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "The benefits and importance of lawns", "html": "<p>Lawns are <b>used</b> in many ways, e.g. as sports surfaces (football pitch, golf course), as play and lounging areas for recreation, and as ornamental greenery in front gardens and parks; they also stabilise embankments.</p><p>In addition, they are of great <b>ecological importance</b>:</p><ul><li>They produce oxygen and bind carbon dioxide as well as dust.</li><li>They cool their surroundings through evaporation (temperature balancing).</li><li>They store water, promote infiltration and thus protect the groundwater.</li><li>They stabilise the soil (erosion protection), reduce noise and provide habitat as well as recreation.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "RSM and the most important lawn grasses", "html": "<p><b>RSM</b> stands for <i>Regel-Saatgut-Mischung</i> (standard seed mixture, a certified lawn-seed mix). These are tested, standardised seed mixtures with a firmly defined composition and quality. For every type of lawn there is a suitable RSM (e.g. RSM 1 ornamental lawn, RSM 2 general-purpose lawn, RSM 3 sports lawn), so that you can reliably choose the right seed.</p><p>Important lawn grasses (with botanical name):</p><table><tr><th>Botanical name</th><th>Common name</th><th>Characteristic</th></tr><tr><td><i>Lolium perenne</i></td><td>perennial ryegrass</td><td>germinates quickly, very hard-wearing – for sports/general-purpose lawns</td></tr><tr><td><i>Poa pratensis</i></td><td>smooth meadow-grass / Kentucky bluegrass</td><td>forms runners (rhizomes), very regenerative and hard-wearing</td></tr><tr><td><i>Festuca rubra</i></td><td>red fescue</td><td>fine-leaved, tolerant of drought and shade</td></tr><tr><td><i>Agrostis capillaris</i></td><td>common bentgrass</td><td>very fine-leaved, for low mowing (ornamental lawn/golf)</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "Establishing a lawn: sowing by hand", "html": "<p>In the hand-sowing (broadcast seeding) method, the lawn is established from seed. The steps in the correct order:</p><ul><li><b>Clearing:</b> remove stones, roots and weeds.</li><li><b>Loosening/tilling:</b> dig over or rotavate the soil so that roots, water and air can penetrate.</li><li><b>Soil analysis:</b> determine the pH value (ideally approx. 5.5–6.5).</li><li><b>Soil improvement:</b> if needed, work in compost or sand, apply base fertiliser.</li><li><b>Rough grading:</b> level the area roughly.</li><li><b>Compacting:</b> press down/roll so that no settlement (hollows) occurs later.</li><li><b>Fine grading:</b> use a rake to create a fine, even surface.</li><li><b>Sowing + starter feeding:</b> spread the seed evenly, apply starter fertiliser.</li><li><b>Working in/raking in:</b> only rake the seed in shallowly – lawn grasses are light germinators.</li><li><b>Rolling:</b> roll to ensure good soil contact.</li><li><b>Watering:</b> water with a fine spray and keep moist until germination – <b>without puddles</b>.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Ready-grown lawn (turf/sod)", "html": "<p>Ready-grown lawn (turf/sod) is pre-cultivated, fully grown lawn that is delivered as grass sods or rolls. The advantage: the area is instantly green and can be used very quickly.</p><p><b>Work steps:</b> The soil is prepared as for sowing (clearing, loosening, soil improvement, compacting, fine grading). Then the rolls are laid tightly and in a bonded pattern (like brickwork) – with staggered joints, without continuous cross-joints. Afterwards press down/roll and immediately water thoroughly. Mowing is only done once the lawn has taken root.</p><p><b>Season:</b> possible almost all year round, except during frost or when the ground is frozen; spring is ideal (autumn also works). Turf is perishable and should be laid quickly (within 1–2 days).</p>"}, {"heading": "Lawn care: establishment care vs. maintenance care", "html": "<p>Five important <b>care measures</b> are: mowing, fertilising, watering, scarifying (dethatching) and aerating (plus top dressing with sand and overseeding).</p><p>Two phases of care are distinguished:</p><ul><li><b>Establishment care (completion care):</b> the care directly after installation <b>up to acceptance (handover)</b>. It brings the lawn into an acceptable, functional condition (first mowing, watering, overseeding of bare patches, starter feeding) and is still part of the construction contract.</li><li><b>Maintenance care:</b> the ongoing, recurring care <b>after acceptance (handover)</b>, in order to preserve the condition in the long term (regular mowing, fertilising, scarifying, etc.). It is a separate, ongoing contract.</li></ul>"}, {"heading": "Mowing: equipment and why we mow", "html": "<p>Regular <b>mowing</b> stimulates tillering (the formation of side shoots), so that a dense, closed sward forms. It keeps the desired height, suppresses weeds and ensures an even appearance.</p><table><tr><th>Mowing machine</th><th>Feature / use</th></tr><tr><td>Rotary mower</td><td>rotating blade, the most common lawn mower</td></tr><tr><td>Bar mower (sickle-bar mower)</td><td>cutter bar, for tall meadows/landscape lawns</td></tr><tr><td>Brush cutter (strimmer)</td><td>power scythe with line/blade, for edges and hard-to-reach spots</td></tr><tr><td>Cylinder mower (reel mower)</td><td>cuts scissor-like against a bottom blade – <b>cleanest/finest cut</b> (ornamental lawn/golf)</td></tr><tr><td>Flail mower</td><td>shreds tall growth, for embankments and overgrown areas</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "Fertilising: nutrients, nitrogen and the risk of scorching", "html": "<p><b>Why fertilise?</b> Mowing constantly removes nutrients from the lawn. Fertilising returns them and ensures a dense, vigorously green, resilient sward that copes better with drought, disease and weeds.</p><p>The most important nutrient is <b>nitrogen (N)</b> – it promotes leaf growth and green colour. A well-known mineral NPK compound fertiliser is <i>Blaukorn</i> (blue-grain compound fertiliser).</p><p><b>Caution:</b> If fertiliser is applied unevenly, the lawn can scorch (burn) at over-fertilised spots (brown stripes), producing an uneven, streaky appearance. Therefore apply evenly (spreader).</p>"}, {"heading": "Scarifying, aerating and top dressing with sand", "html": "<table><tr><th>Measure</th><th>Aim</th></tr><tr><td><b>Scarifying (dethatching)</b></td><td>vertical scoring of the sward; removes thatch, moss and mowing residue; improves the supply of air, water and nutrients; stimulates tillering</td></tr><tr><td><b>Aerating</b></td><td>ventilating by punching out small soil cores/holes; loosens compacted soil; improves the supply of air and water to the roots</td></tr><tr><td><b>Top dressing with sand</b></td><td>applying sand; improves water permeability (drainage), evens out unevenness, reduces thatch build-up – often after aerating</td></tr></table>"}], "exam": [{"q": "What is a lawn and which four types of lawn are distinguished?", "answer": "A lawn is a dense, closed area of lawn grasses kept short by regular mowing. Four types are distinguished: <b>ornamental lawn</b> (fine-leaved, low wear tolerance, purely decorative), <b>general-purpose lawn</b> (a robust all-rounder for home gardens and parks), <b>hard-wearing lawn</b> (tread-resistant, for sports and play areas) and <b>landscape lawn</b> (extensive, for embankments and near-natural areas).", "hints": ["Think of a dense, closely mown grass surface – and that it is classified by use and wear tolerance.", "There are exactly four types, from 'purely to look at' to 'extensive/near-natural'.", "The first three name the degree of wear (ornamental..., general-purpose..., hard-wearing...), the fourth concerns embankments/nature (landscape...)."]}, {"q": "Name three examples of the use of lawns.", "answer": "For example: sports surfaces (football pitch or golf course), play and lounging areas for recreation, and ornamental greenery in front gardens and parks; also the stabilisation of embankments.", "hints": ["Think about what people use lawns for in everyday life.", "Sport, leisure/recreation and appearance are three major areas.", "Name specifically e.g. a football pitch, a lawn for lounging and an ornamental lawn in the front garden."]}, {"q": "Name four positive properties, or the importance, of lawns.", "answer": "A lawn produces oxygen and binds CO₂ as well as dust; it cools through evaporation (temperature balancing); it stores water and promotes infiltration (groundwater protection); and it stabilises the soil (erosion protection), reduces noise and provides recreation as well as habitat.", "hints": ["Think of air, water, soil and climate.", "Keywords: oxygen/dust, cooling, water/infiltration, erosion protection.", "Four are enough – e.g. oxygen production, temperature balancing, water storage and soil stabilisation."]}, {"q": "Match each of the four types of lawn with a typical use and its wear tolerance.", "answer": "<b>Ornamental lawn</b> – ornamental areas/front gardens – low wear tolerance, high maintenance. <b>General-purpose lawn</b> – home gardens, parks, public green spaces – medium wear tolerance, low-maintenance. <b>Hard-wearing lawn</b> – sports, play and lounging areas – high wear tolerance, tread-resistant, regenerative. <b>Landscape lawn</b> – embankments, roadside greenery, near-natural areas – low wear tolerance, extensive/low-maintenance.", "hints": ["Go through the four types one by one and ask yourself: where is it located, and how much wear can it withstand?", "Remember: ornamental = beautiful but delicate; hard-wearing = the most robust.", "Matching: ornamental lawn→front garden/low, general-purpose lawn→home garden/medium, hard-wearing lawn→sports ground/high, landscape lawn→embankment/low."]}, {"q": "What does the abbreviation RSM stand for?", "answer": "RSM stands for <b><i>Regel-Saatgut-Mischung</i></b> (standard seed mixture) – a tested, standardised seed mixture with a defined composition and quality that contains the right grasses for each type of lawn.", "hints": ["It is about the seed that you buy.", "Three words; in German the last two – Saatgut-Mischung – mean 'seed mixture'.", "The first word emphasises the norm/standard: Regel (standard) in Regel-Saatgut-Mischung."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'Before sowing, the soil must be loosened.'", "answer": "<b>True.</b> The soil must be loosened (dug over or rotavated) so that the roots can penetrate well and both water and air can get into the soil.", "hints": ["Consider whether roots grow better in firm or in loose soil.", "Without loosening there is no good rooting – so the statement is true."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'On heavy or nutrient-poor soils, compost can be worked in.'", "answer": "<b>True.</b> Compost improves the soil structure and supplies nutrients; it is worked in to improve the soil.", "hints": ["Compost is a classic means of improving soil.", "Organic material benefits the soil – so the statement is true."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'To prevent settlement later, the soil is rolled or compacted before sowing.'", "answer": "<b>True.</b> By pressing down/rolling (or treading it firm), the soil settles evenly, so that no settlement (hollows) occurs later.", "hints": ["'Settlement' means later sinking or hollows in the soil.", "If you press the soil down beforehand, it sinks less later – so true."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'The best time to sow is midsummer in blazing heat.'", "answer": "<b>False.</b> Spring and late summer/early autumn are ideal, with moderate temperatures and sufficient moisture; in heat and drought the lawn germinates poorly. The soil temperature should exceed about 8–10 °C.", "hints": ["Young seedlings need moisture – does that fit with blazing summer heat?", "Think of spring and late summer instead of midsummer – so the statement is false."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'Lawn seed is placed several centimetres deep into the soil.'", "answer": "<b>False.</b> Lawn grasses are light germinators; the seed is only raked in very shallowly (about 0.5–1 cm), not buried deep.", "hints": ["Some seeds need light to germinate – they are called light germinators.", "Buried deep, or only lightly raked in? The statement is false."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'You should use tested seed conforming to RSM.'", "answer": "<b>True.</b> Tested standard seed mixtures (RSM) guarantee the right, high-quality grass composition for each type of lawn.", "hints": ["RSM stands for a tested, standardised mixture.", "Tested, standard-compliant seed is recommended – so true."]}, {"q": "True or false? 'When watering after sowing, it is fine for puddles to form.'", "answer": "<b>False.</b> Watering must be fine and even, without puddles forming – otherwise the light seed is washed away and collects unevenly.", "hints": ["What happens to light seeds when water pools into puddles?", "Water with a fine spray rather than flooding – so with puddles the statement is false."]}, {"q": "Name the steps of hand-sowing in the correct order.", "answer": "1) <b>Clear</b> the area (stones, roots, weeds), 2) <b>loosen/rotavate</b> the soil, 3) <b>soil analysis</b> – determine the pH value, 4) <b>soil improvement</b> (compost/sand, base fertilising), 5) create the <b>rough grading</b>, 6) <b>compact</b>/press down (against settlement), 7) create the <b>fine grading</b>, 8) <b>sow and starter-feed</b> evenly, 9) <b>rake in/work in</b> the seed (shallow, light germinators), 10) <b>roll</b> (soil contact), 11) <b>water</b>/keep moist until germination.", "hints": ["Start with the bare soil (clearing, loosening) and end with watering.", "Compacting takes place between rough and fine grading; sowing comes only after fine grading.", "Rough order: clear → loosen → pH/soil improvement → rough grading → compact → fine grading → sow+fertilise → rake in → roll → water."]}, {"q": "What is meant by ready-grown lawn (turf/sod), and in which season is it laid?", "answer": "Ready-grown lawn (turf/sod) is pre-cultivated, fully grown lawn that is delivered and laid as grass sods or rolls; as a result the area is instantly green and can be used very quickly. It can be laid almost <b>all year round</b>, <b>except during frost</b> or when the ground is frozen; <b>spring</b> is ideal (autumn as well). Turf is perishable and should be laid quickly (within 1–2 days).", "hints": ["Instead of sowing, ready-made lawn is rolled out here.", "Possible all year round – except for one condition that has to do with cold.", "'Except during frost, ideal in spring' – and the advantage: instantly green and usable."]}, {"q": "Describe the steps for laying ready-grown lawn (turf).", "answer": "First the soil is prepared as for sowing (clearing, loosening, soil improvement, compacting, fine grading). Then the rolls are laid tightly and in a bonded pattern (staggered joints, no continuous cross-joints), pressed down or rolled for good soil contact and immediately watered thoroughly. Mowing is only done once the lawn has taken root.", "hints": ["The soil must be prepared beforehand in exactly the same way as for sowing.", "Lay the rolls tightly – stagger the joints as in a brick bond.", "After laying: press down/roll and water thoroughly straight away."]}, {"q": "Name five care measures for a lawn.", "answer": "Mowing, fertilising, watering, scarifying and aerating (ventilating); also top dressing with sand and overseeding.", "hints": ["The most frequent, most regular measure begins with 'M' (mowing).", "Think of cutting, feeding, watering and ventilating.", "Mowing, fertilising, watering, scarifying, aerating – five are enough."]}, {"q": "Explain the difference between establishment care and maintenance care.", "answer": "<b>Establishment care</b> is the care directly after installation <b>up to acceptance (handover)</b> – it brings the lawn into an acceptable, functional condition (first mowing, watering, overseeding of bare patches, starter feeding) and is still part of the construction contract. <b>Maintenance care</b> is the ongoing, recurring care <b>after acceptance (handover)</b>, in order to preserve the condition in the long term (regular mowing, fertilising, scarifying, etc.); it is a separate, ongoing contract.", "hints": ["The difference lies in the timing: one-off after installation vs. ongoing afterwards.", "One term ends at acceptance (handover), the other only really begins afterwards.", "Establishment care = up to acceptance (part of the construction); maintenance care = ongoing afterwards."]}, {"q": "Name five mowing machines and state which one delivers the cleanest cut.", "answer": "Rotary mower, bar mower, brush cutter (power scythe), cylinder mower and flail mower. The <b>cleanest/finest cut</b> is delivered by the <b>cylinder mower</b> (reel mower), because it cuts scissor-like against a bottom blade.", "hints": ["Think of the ordinary lawn mower, the power scythe and machines for tall meadows/embankments.", "Five types: rotary, bar, brush (cutter), cylinder, flail...", "The 'cylinder mower' cuts like scissors – hence the cleanest cut."]}, {"q": "Why do we mow a lawn?", "answer": "Mowing stimulates tillering (the formation of side shoots), so that a dense, closed sward forms. It keeps the desired height, suppresses emerging weeds and ensures an even, well-kept appearance.", "hints": ["Regular cutting does not make the lawn thinner, but rather...", "It promotes side shoots (tillering) and thus density.", "Aims: a dense sward, the right height and fewer weeds."]}, {"q": "Why do we fertilise a lawn?", "answer": "Fertilising supplies the nutrients that the lawn needs for growth and regeneration and that are constantly removed from it by mowing. This produces a dense, vigorously green and resilient sward that copes better with drought, disease and weeds.", "hints": ["Mowing constantly takes something away from the lawn – what has to be replaced?", "Nutrients ensure density, green colour and resilience."]}, {"q": "What is the consequence of uneven fertilising?", "answer": "With uneven fertilising, the lawn can scorch (burn) at over-fertilised spots (scorch marks, brown stripes), and an uneven appearance results with light and dark, or streaky, areas.", "hints": ["Too much fertiliser in one spot harms the grass.", "The grass can 'scorch' – and the appearance becomes streaky."]}, {"q": "Which nutrient is most important for the lawn, and what is the name of a well-known mineral compound fertiliser?", "answer": "The most important nutrient is <b>nitrogen (N)</b>; it promotes leaf growth and the green colour. A well-known mineral NPK compound fertiliser is <b><i>Blaukorn</i></b> (blue-grain compound fertiliser).", "hints": ["This nutrient makes the lawn green and lets the leaves grow.", "Its chemical symbol is 'N'.", "Nitrogen (N); a well-known blue compound fertiliser is called Blaukorn."]}, {"q": "What is the aim of scarifying?", "answer": "In scarifying, the sward is scored vertically in order to remove thatch, moss and mowing residue. This improves the supply of air, water and nutrients and stimulates tillering.", "hints": ["It is about removing thatch and moss from the lawn.", "In doing so, the sward is scored vertically.", "Result: less thatch/moss, a better air and water balance."]}, {"q": "What is the aim of aerating?", "answer": "In aerating, the soil is ventilated by punching out small soil cores or holes. This loosens compacted soil and improves the supply of air and water to the roots.", "hints": ["The word comes from the Latin 'aer' = air.", "You punch holes or cores into the soil.", "Aim: to ventilate compacted soil and supply the roots better."]}, {"q": "What is the aim of top dressing with sand?", "answer": "In top dressing with sand, sand is applied to the area. This improves water permeability (drainage), evens out unevenness and reduces thatch build-up; it is often done following aerating.", "hints": ["You spread a certain material thinly over the lawn.", "Sand improves water drainage and levels the area.", "Often after aerating, to fill the holes and improve drainage."]}, {"q": "Name four important lawn grasses with their botanical and common name.", "answer": "<i>Lolium perenne</i> – perennial ryegrass (fast-germinating, hard-wearing); <i>Poa pratensis</i> – smooth meadow-grass / Kentucky bluegrass (forms runners, very regenerative); <i>Festuca rubra</i> – red fescue (fine-leaved, tolerant of drought and shade); <i>Agrostis capillaris</i> – common bentgrass (very fine-leaved, for low mowing).", "hints": ["There are four Latin names, with Lolium, Poa, Festuca and Agrostis.", "Think of ryegrass, meadow-grass, fescue and bentgrass.", "Lolium perenne = perennial ryegrass, Poa pratensis = smooth meadow-grass, Festuca rubra = red fescue, Agrostis capillaris = common bentgrass."]}]}, "pflanzenkenntnisse": {"id": "pflanzenkenntnisse", "title": "Plant Knowledge – Exam Essentials", "intro": "Plant knowledge means being able to identify plants reliably by their full botanical name (genus, species, cultivar) and to match them with characteristics such as fruit colour, flowering time, growth habit and use. This module brings together the exam-relevant knowledge on woody plants, perennials, ferns, clipped hedges and pines.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "The Botanical Name: Genus, Species and Cultivar", "html": "<p>In plant identification, every plant is named by its <b>full botanical name</b>. It consists of three parts:</p><ul><li><b>Genus</b> – capitalised, italic (e.g. <i>Berberis</i>).</li><li><b>Species</b> – lower case, italic (e.g. <i>thunbergii</i>).</li><li><b>Cultivar</b> – upright (roman) and in single quotation marks (e.g. <i>Berberis thunbergii</i> 'Atropurpurea').</li></ul><p>This basic two-part system (binomial nomenclature) goes back to Carl von Linné. In the exam you must identify plants by this name and match them with characteristics such as fruit colour, flowering time and growth habit.</p>"}, {"heading": "Fruit Colours of Important Woody Plants", "html": "<p>A woody plant can often be identified by the colour of its fruit – sometimes the species name itself reveals the colour (<i>albus</i> = white).</p><table><tr><td><i>Symphoricarpos albus</i> (snowberry)</td><td>white</td></tr><tr><td><i>Hippophae rhamnoides</i> (sea buckthorn)</td><td>orange</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ilex aquifolium</i> (holly)</td><td>red</td></tr><tr><td><i>Chaenomeles japonica</i> (Japanese quince)</td><td>yellow</td></tr><tr><td><i>Berberis thunbergii</i> (barberry)</td><td>red</td></tr><tr><td><i>Mahonia aquifolium</i> (Oregon grape)</td><td>blue (with a waxy bloom)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Parthenocissus quinquefolia</i> (Virginia creeper)</td><td>blue-black</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "Woody Plants by Flowering Time", "html": "<p>For a good planting design, something should be in flower throughout the whole year. Remember a few key woody plants for each season and their flowering time:</p><table><tr><td><b>Winter (Nov–March)</b></td><td><i>Hamamelis mollis</i> (witch hazel), <i>Viburnum ×bodnantense</i> (fragrant viburnum)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Spring</b></td><td><i>Corylus avellana</i> (hazel), <i>Magnolia ×soulangeana</i> (saucer magnolia), <i>Forsythia</i> (forsythia)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Early summer</b></td><td><i>Robinia pseudoacacia</i> (black locust), <i>Kolkwitzia amabilis</i> (beauty bush)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Summer/Autumn</b></td><td><i>Buddleja davidii</i> (butterfly bush), <i>Hibiscus syriacus</i> (rose of Sharon), <i>Calluna vulgaris</i> (heather)</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "Perennials: Yellow-Flowering Types and Cushion-Forming Rock Garden Perennials", "html": "<p>A herbaceous perennial is a plant that lives for several years; in winter it usually dies back above ground and puts out new growth again in spring.</p><p><b>Four yellow-flowering perennials:</b> <i>Sedum acre</i> (biting stonecrop), <i>Coreopsis verticillata</i> (tickseed), <i>Eranthis hyemalis</i> (winter aconite), <i>Achillea filipendulina</i> (fern-leaf yarrow).</p><p><b>Cushion-forming rock garden perennials by flower colour:</b></p><table><tr><td>white</td><td><i>Arabis caucasica</i> (rock cress)</td></tr><tr><td>blue</td><td><i>Ajuga reptans</i> (creeping bugle), <i>Aubrieta</i> (aubretia)</td></tr><tr><td>yellow</td><td><i>Aurinia saxatilis</i> (basket-of-gold)</td></tr><tr><td>pink/red</td><td><i>Thymus serpyllum</i> (wild thyme), <i>Dianthus</i> (pink)</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "Ground Covers, Ferns and Clipped Hedges", "html": "<p><b>Four ground-covering woody plants or subshrubs with showy flowers:</b> <i>Lavandula angustifolia</i> (lavender), <i>Vinca minor</i> (lesser periwinkle), <i>Potentilla fruticosa</i> (shrubby cinquefoil), <i>Hypericum calycinum</i> (St John's wort).</p><p><b>Two hardy outdoor ferns:</b> <i>Dryopteris filix-mas</i> (common male fern), <i>Polystichum setiferum</i> (soft shield fern). Ferns do not flower but reproduce by spores.</p><p><b>Two evergreen/wintergreen clipped hedges:</b> <i>Taxus baccata</i> (yew, evergreen, poisonous) and <i>Ligustrum vulgare</i> (privet, wintergreen to semi-evergreen). Both tolerate clipping very well.</p>"}, {"heading": "Telling Pines (Pinus) Apart", "html": "<p>Pines are easy to identify by the number of needles per bundle (fascicle) and by their growth habit:</p><table><tr><td>native (Scots pine)</td><td><i>Pinus sylvestris</i> – 2 needles per bundle</td></tr><tr><td>shrubby, low-growing (mountain / mugo pine)</td><td><i>Pinus mugo</i> – 2 needles per bundle</td></tr><tr><td>needles in fives per bundle</td><td><i>Pinus cembra</i> (Swiss stone pine / Arolla pine), <i>Pinus wallichiana</i> (Bhutan / Himalayan pine)</td></tr></table><p>Remember: the two native/shrubby species have 2 needles, while the 'noble' 5-needle species are the Swiss stone pine and the Bhutan pine.</p>"}], "exam": [{"q": "Which three parts make up the full botanical name of a plant? Explain them briefly using an example.", "answer": "The full botanical name consists of <b>genus</b>, <b>species</b> and <b>cultivar</b>. The genus is written with a capital letter and in italics, the species in lower case and italics, and the cultivar upright and in single quotation marks. Example: <i>Berberis</i> (genus) <i>thunbergii</i> (species) 'Atropurpurea' (cultivar).", "hints": ["Think of Carl von Linné's classification system – how many words does a plant name need as a minimum?", "The first part is the higher-level group, the second names the specific plant within that group.", "The third part is a cultivated selection and is written in single quotation marks, e.g. 'Atropurpurea'."]}, {"q": "Match the following woody plants with their fruit colour: Symphoricarpos albus, Hippophae rhamnoides, Ilex aquifolium, Chaenomeles japonica, Berberis thunbergii, Mahonia aquifolium, Parthenocissus quinquefolia.", "answer": "<i>Symphoricarpos albus</i> = white; <i>Hippophae rhamnoides</i> = orange; <i>Ilex aquifolium</i> = red; <i>Chaenomeles japonica</i> = yellow; <i>Berberis thunbergii</i> = red; <i>Mahonia aquifolium</i> = blue (with a waxy bloom); <i>Parthenocissus quinquefolia</i> = blue-black.", "hints": ["For some, the species name itself reveals the colour – 'albus' means white.", "Sea buckthorn (Hippophae) glows orange; holly (Ilex) and barberry (Berberis) bear red fruit.", "Oregon grape (Mahonia) and Virginia creeper have blue and blue-black berries respectively, while the Japanese quince (Chaenomeles) is yellow."]}, {"q": "Name four yellow-flowering perennials.", "answer": "Four yellow-flowering perennials are: <i>Sedum acre</i> (biting stonecrop), <i>Coreopsis verticillata</i> (tickseed), <i>Eranthis hyemalis</i> (winter aconite) and <i>Achillea filipendulina</i> (fern-leaf yarrow).", "hints": ["Think of rock garden and border perennials with sunny yellow flowers.", "A very early spring bloomer is the winter aconite (Eranthis hyemalis).", "Others are biting stonecrop (Sedum acre), tickseed (Coreopsis verticillata) and fern-leaf yarrow (Achillea filipendulina)."]}, {"q": "Match the following woody plants with the correct flowering time (Winter/Nov–March, Spring, Early summer, Summer/Autumn): Hamamelis mollis, Viburnum bodnantense, Corylus avellana, Magnolia soulangeana, Forsythia, Robinia pseudoacacia, Kolkwitzia amabilis, Buddleja davidii, Hibiscus syriacus, Calluna vulgaris.", "answer": "<b>Winter (Nov–March):</b> <i>Hamamelis mollis</i>, <i>Viburnum ×bodnantense</i>. <b>Spring:</b> <i>Corylus avellana</i>, <i>Magnolia ×soulangeana</i>, <i>Forsythia</i>. <b>Early summer:</b> <i>Robinia pseudoacacia</i>, <i>Kolkwitzia amabilis</i>. <b>Summer/Autumn:</b> <i>Buddleja davidii</i>, <i>Hibiscus syriacus</i>, <i>Calluna vulgaris</i>.", "hints": ["Two flower as early as winter, when hardly anything is in bloom – witch hazel and fragrant viburnum.", "Hazel, saucer magnolia and forsythia usher in the spring.", "Black locust and beauty bush flower in early summer; butterfly bush, rose of Sharon and heather not until summer/autumn."]}, {"q": "Match the cushion-forming rock garden perennials with their flower colour (white, blue, yellow, pink/red): Arabis caucasica, Ajuga reptans, Aubrieta, Aurinia saxatilis, Thymus serpyllum, Dianthus.", "answer": "<b>White:</b> <i>Arabis caucasica</i> (rock cress). <b>Blue:</b> <i>Ajuga reptans</i> (creeping bugle), <i>Aubrieta</i> (aubretia). <b>Yellow:</b> <i>Aurinia saxatilis</i> (basket-of-gold). <b>Pink/red:</b> <i>Thymus serpyllum</i> (wild thyme), <i>Dianthus</i> (pink).", "hints": ["The rock cress (Arabis caucasica) flowers white.", "Creeping bugle (Ajuga) and aubretia (Aubrieta) flower blue, while basket-of-gold (Aurinia saxatilis) glows yellow.", "Wild thyme (Thymus serpyllum) and pink (Dianthus) flower pink to red."]}, {"q": "Name four ground-covering woody plants or subshrubs with showy flowers.", "answer": "Four ground-covering woody plants/subshrubs with showy flowers are: <i>Lavandula angustifolia</i> (true lavender), <i>Vinca minor</i> (lesser periwinkle), <i>Potentilla fruticosa</i> (shrubby cinquefoil) and <i>Hypericum calycinum</i> (St John's wort).", "hints": ["You are looking for spreading, low-growing woody plants with clearly visible flowers.", "A fragrant subshrub with violet flowers is the true lavender.", "Others are lesser periwinkle (Vinca minor), shrubby cinquefoil (Potentilla fruticosa) and St John's wort (Hypericum calycinum)."]}, {"q": "Name two hardy outdoor ferns.", "answer": "Two outdoor ferns are <i>Dryopteris filix-mas</i> (common male fern) and <i>Polystichum setiferum</i> (soft shield fern). Ferns do not flower but reproduce by spores.", "hints": ["Ferns have no flowers but reproduce by spores.", "A very common native fern is the male fern.", "Botanically: Dryopteris filix-mas and Polystichum setiferum."]}, {"q": "Name two evergreen or wintergreen woody plants suitable for use as a clipped hedge.", "answer": "Two suitable clipped hedges are <i>Taxus baccata</i> (yew, evergreen) and <i>Ligustrum vulgare</i> (privet, wintergreen to semi-evergreen). Both tolerate clipping very well.", "hints": ["You are looking for clipping-tolerant woody plants that keep their leaves or needles even in winter.", "A classic, poisonous coniferous hedge plant is the yew.", "Botanically: Taxus baccata (evergreen) and Ligustrum vulgare (wintergreen)."]}, {"q": "Match the pine species to the relevant characteristic: native, shrubby/low-growing, five needles per bundle.", "answer": "<b>Native:</b> <i>Pinus sylvestris</i> (Scots pine). <b>Shrubby/low-growing:</b> <i>Pinus mugo</i> (mountain / mugo pine). <b>Five needles per bundle:</b> <i>Pinus cembra</i> (Swiss stone pine / Arolla pine) and <i>Pinus wallichiana</i> (Bhutan / Himalayan pine).", "hints": ["The pine native to our region is also called the Scots pine.", "The low, shrubby species is the mountain pine (Pinus mugo).", "The Swiss stone pine (Pinus cembra) and the Bhutan pine (Pinus wallichiana) have five needles per bundle; Pinus sylvestris is the native one."]}]}, "sozialversicherung": {"id": "sozialversicherung", "title": "Social insurance – the 5 principles", "intro": "German social insurance protects people from the major risks of life such as illness, old age, the need for long-term care, unemployment and accident. Five basic principles explain who pays for the benefits and what they are based on – from contribution-financed insurance to tax-financed welfare.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "Overview: the 5 principles", "html": "<p>German social insurance is based on five basic principles. They answer two questions: <b>Who pays?</b> and <b>What is the benefit based on?</b></p><p>The five principles can be divided into two groups:</p><ul><li><b>Contribution-financed</b> (from contributions + state subsidies): the insurance, equivalence and solidarity principle.</li><li><b>Tax-financed</b> (from tax revenue): the provision and welfare principle.</li></ul><p>Remember: with the contribution-financed principles, you have paid in yourself. With the tax-financed ones, you receive benefits without your own contributions – either in return for service to the state or out of sheer need.</p>"}, {"heading": "Insurance principle", "html": "<p>Anyone who pays contributions acquires a legal entitlement to benefits. In this way you are insured against risks such as illness, the need for long-term care, unemployment, accident and old age.</p><p>Important: the benefit is <b>not</b> given out of pity, but because you have paid for it. The insurance principle is the shared basis of statutory health, long-term care, pension, unemployment and accident insurance.</p>"}, {"heading": "Equivalence principle", "html": "<p>\"Equivalence\" means equal value: contribution and benefit are proportionate to each other. <b>Whoever pays in more also gets more out.</b></p><p>A typical example is the statutory pension: high, long-paid contributions lead to a high pension. The equivalence principle is, so to speak, the \"I get what I am entitled to\" side of insurance.</p>"}, {"heading": "Solidarity principle", "html": "<p>The community of insured members bears the risks together: <b>the strong help the weak.</b> The contribution is based on income, but the benefit is based on need.</p><p>That is why a high earner and a low earner receive the same treatment for the same illness – even though they pay different amounts in contributions. The healthy help carry the sick, the young help carry the old, and the childless help carry families.</p>"}, {"heading": "Provision principle", "html": "<p>The state grants benefits <b>without prior contributions</b> – as consideration for special service or for a special sacrifice made for the benefit of the general public. This is financed from tax revenue.</p><p>Examples: pension benefits for civil servants (a pension) for tenured civil servants, pensions for war victims, or a victim's pension for people who are harmed in state service.</p>"}, {"heading": "Welfare principle", "html": "<p>The state helps people in need who cannot help themselves and have no other entitlements. The condition is a means test: only someone who has no sufficient income and assets receives help.</p><p>Examples are social assistance and <i>Grundsicherung</i> (basic income support). The welfare principle, too, is financed from tax revenue, not from contributions.</p>"}, {"heading": "Financing – who pays?", "html": "<table><tr><th>Principle</th><th>Financing</th><th>Condition</th></tr><tr><td>Insurance / equivalence / solidarity</td><td>Contributions + state subsidies</td><td>own contributions</td></tr><tr><td>Provision</td><td>Tax revenue</td><td>service or sacrifice for the state</td></tr><tr><td>Welfare</td><td>Tax revenue</td><td>neediness</td></tr></table>"}, {"heading": "How to identify the principle quickly", "html": "<ul><li>Were <b>contributions</b> paid? → Insurance / equivalence / solidarity.</li><li>Does everyone get <b>the same amount</b> despite different contributions? → <b>Solidarity</b>.</li><li>Does someone get <b>more</b> because they paid in more? → <b>Equivalence</b>.</li><li>A benefit <b>without contributions</b> as thanks/compensation for state service or a sacrifice? → <b>Provision</b>.</li><li>A benefit <b>without contributions</b> only because of neediness (means test)? → <b>Welfare</b>.</li></ul>"}], "exam": [{"q": "Gerlinde pays 270 EUR/month into health insurance, Patrick only 120 EUR. For the same operation, both receive exactly the same benefit. Which principle applies? Give reasons.", "answer": "Here the <b>solidarity principle</b> applies. Gerlinde and Patrick pay different amounts in contributions (270 EUR and 120 EUR respectively), because the contribution is based on income. The benefit, on the other hand, is based on need: for the same operation both receive the same treatment. In this way the stronger help carry the weaker.", "hints": ["Note that the two pay in different amounts but are treated equally.", "The contribution is based on income, but the benefit is based on need.", "The strong help the weak – the principle you are looking for begins with \"solid…\"."]}, {"q": "Henriette paid high contributions for 40 years and receives a higher pension than Mathilde, who paid in only a little. Which principle applies? Give reasons.", "answer": "Here the <b>equivalence principle</b> applies. Contribution and benefit are proportionate to each other (equal value): Henriette paid high contributions for 40 years and therefore receives a higher pension than Mathilde, who paid in only a little. Whoever pays in more gets more out.", "hints": ["The amount of the pension here depends directly on something.", "Whoever pays in more gets more out – contribution and benefit correspond to each other.", "The Latin word for \"equal value\" is contained in the name: equi…"]}, {"q": "Jana has neither income nor assets and receives social assistance. Which principle applies? Give reasons.", "answer": "Here the <b>welfare principle</b> applies. Jana has not paid any contributions of her own. Because she has neither income nor assets, the state helps her from tax revenue. After a means test she receives social assistance.", "hints": ["Jana has not paid any contributions beforehand.", "She receives help because she is in need – financed from taxes.", "The state looks after people in need – the principle begins with \"wel…\"."]}, {"q": "Annette is a tenured teacher and receives civil-service pension benefits (a pension) in old age. Which principle applies? Give reasons.", "answer": "Here the <b>provision principle</b> applies. As a tenured teacher, Annette does not pay any contributions into the statutory pension insurance. Her pension benefits for civil servants (a pension) are compensation from the state for her service and are financed from tax revenue.", "hints": ["Annette is a civil servant – she does not pay into the statutory pension insurance.", "Her pension is compensation from the state for her service, paid from taxes.", "Civil servants are provided for by the state – the principle begins with \"prov…\"."]}, {"q": "Franzl contracts an illness in state service and receives a victim's pension for it. Which principle applies? Give reasons.", "answer": "Here the <b>provision principle</b> applies. Franzl suffered an illness in state service. The victim's pension is compensation for this special sacrifice for the benefit of the general public. It is paid without prior contributions, from tax revenue.", "hints": ["Franzl worked for the state and was harmed in the process.", "The victim's pension is compensation for a special sacrifice in state service – without prior contributions, from taxes.", "As with the civil-servant pension, the prov… principle applies here."]}, {"q": "Name the five principles of social insurance.", "answer": "The five principles are: the <b>insurance principle</b>, the <b>equivalence principle</b>, the <b>solidarity principle</b>, the <b>provision principle</b> and the <b>welfare principle</b>. The first three are financed from contributions and state subsidies, the last two from tax revenue.", "hints": ["There are five – three are financed from contributions, two from taxes.", "The contribution-financed group comprises the insurance, equivalence and solidarity principle.", "The two tax-financed ones are the prov… and wel… principle."]}, {"q": "How are the individual principles financed? Assign the correct principles to the two types of financing (contributions + state subsidies, and tax revenue).", "answer": "The <b>insurance principle</b>, the <b>equivalence principle</b> and the <b>solidarity principle</b> are financed from contributions and state subsidies. The <b>provision principle</b> and the <b>welfare principle</b> are financed from tax revenue.", "hints": ["There are two sources of financing: contributions and taxes.", "All principles where you have paid in yourself belong to the same group.", "Contributions + state subsidies: insurance, equivalence, solidarity. Tax revenue: provision and welfare."]}]}, "arbeitsschutz": {"id": "arbeitsschutz", "title": "Occupational Safety & Machinery", "intro": "What's compulsory on site — protective equipment, power tools and earth-moving machinery.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)", "html": "<p>Personal protective equipment (PPE) in landscaping is not a recommendation but a legal requirement. It protects against the typical hazards on site: falling loads, sharp tools, noise, dust and road traffic.</p><table><tr><th>PSA</th><th>English</th><th>Purpose / when compulsory</th></tr><tr><td><b>Sicherheitsschuhe S3</b></td><td>safety boots S3</td><td>Steel toe cap and puncture-resistant sole – <b>compulsory on every site</b></td></tr><tr><td><b>Arbeitshandschuhe</b></td><td>work gloves</td><td>Protection against cuts and thorns, better grip when carrying stones</td></tr><tr><td><b>Schnittschutzhose</b></td><td>chainsaw trousers</td><td><b>Compulsory for all chainsaw work</b> – the fibres block the chain</td></tr><tr><td><b>Gehörschutz</b></td><td>ear protection</td><td>For all loud machines: mower, saw, plate compactor, chipper</td></tr><tr><td><b>Schutzbrille</b></td><td>safety goggles</td><td>Eye protection when trimming, abrasive cutting and chipping</td></tr><tr><td><b>Forsthelm mit Visier und Gehörschutz</b></td><td>forestry helmet</td><td>Combined protection for tree and chainsaw work (head + face + ears)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Warnweste</b></td><td>high-visibility vest</td><td>Visibility on the road and on site</td></tr><tr><td><b>Knieschoner</b></td><td>knee pads</td><td>Protection when paving and planting</td></tr><tr><td><b>Staubmaske</b></td><td>dust mask</td><td>For dust, stone cutting and when handling substrates</td></tr></table><p><b>Remember:</b> the louder, sharper and faster the machine, the more PPE you need. For the chainsaw the full combination applies: helmet with visor and ear protection, chainsaw trousers, safety boots, gloves.</p>"}, {"heading": "Power tools for cutting and woody-plant care", "html": "<p>The lawn module has already explained rotary, cutter-bar, cylinder and flail mowers, the brushcutter/clearing saw and the scarifier. For the <b>care of trees, shrubs and green spaces</b>, the following machines are still completely missing:</p><table><tr><th>Maschine</th><th>English</th><th>Use</th></tr><tr><td><b>Kettensäge / Motorsäge</b></td><td>chainsaw</td><td>Felling trees, cutting trunks and thick branches to length – only with a <b>Motorsägenschein</b> (chainsaw certificate) and full PPE</td></tr><tr><td><b>Motorheckenschere</b></td><td>power hedge trimmer</td><td>Cutting large hedges (shaping and cutting back)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Rasentrimmer</b></td><td>strimmer / line trimmer</td><td>Fine trimming along edges, borders and around obstacles</td></tr><tr><td><b>Laubbläser</b></td><td>leaf blower</td><td>Blowing leaves and light cuttings into a pile</td></tr><tr><td><b>Laubsauger / Häckselsauger</b></td><td>leaf vacuum</td><td>Vacuuming up leaves and shredding them at the same time (the volume gets smaller)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Häcksler / Schredder</b></td><td>wood chipper / shredder</td><td>Processing branches into wood chips – can be reused as mulch</td></tr><tr><td><b>Bodenfräse / Motorhacke</b></td><td>rotary tiller</td><td>Loosening beds and soil deeply, e.g. before sowing a lawn</td></tr><tr><td><b>Wurzelfräse / Stubbenfräse</b></td><td>stump grinder</td><td>Removing tree stumps without digging out the whole root ball</td></tr><tr><td><b>Hochdruckreiniger</b></td><td>pressure washer</td><td>Cleaning surfaces and equipment (caution: washes out the jointing sand)</td></tr></table><p><b>Important for the Umschulung:</b> the <b>Motorsägenschein</b> is part of the spok course. Without the certificate and without chainsaw trousers, a forestry helmet and safety boots, the chainsaw must not be operated.</p>"}, {"heading": "Earth-moving and compaction machines", "html": "<p>The <b>plate compactor</b> is already explained in the path-building module under the technical term \"compacting\". The following larger machines are still missing:</p><table><tr><th>Maschine</th><th>English</th><th>Use</th></tr><tr><td><b>Rüttelstampfer / Stampfer („Jumping Jack“)</b></td><td>rammer / trench compactor</td><td>Compacting trenches and tight spots – works deeper but narrower than the plate compactor</td></tr><tr><td><b>Minibagger</b></td><td>mini excavator</td><td>Excavation, trenches and earthworks in a tight garden</td></tr><tr><td><b>Radlader / Hoflader</b></td><td>wheel loader</td><td>Moving, picking up and loading material</td></tr><tr><td><b>Dumper / Motorschubkarre</b></td><td>dumper</td><td>Transporting soil and gravel over longer distances</td></tr><tr><td><b>Erdbohrer</b></td><td>earth auger</td><td>Drilling post holes and planting holes</td></tr><tr><td><b>Trennschleifer / Flex</b></td><td>angle grinder / cut-off saw</td><td>Cutting slabs and stones (dry, a lot of dust → dust mask)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Steinschneider / Nassschneider</b></td><td>wet tile saw</td><td>Precise, low-dust cuts for paving and slabs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Bewässerungscomputer</b></td><td>irrigation timer</td><td>Controlling automatic irrigation</td></tr></table><p><b>Remember the difference:</b> plate compactor = compacting a <i>surface</i>, trench rammer = compacting a <i>trench</i>.</p>"}], "exam": [{"q": "Which personal protective equipment (PPE) is required when working with a chainsaw? Name at least five items.", "answer": "<b>Forestry helmet with visor and ear protection</b> (head, face, ears), <b>chainsaw trousers</b> (the fibres block the chain), <b>safety boots S3</b> or chainsaw boots, <b>work gloves</b> and a <b>high-visibility vest</b> when working near the road. For the chainsaw itself, a <b>Motorsägenschein</b> (chainsaw certificate) is required.", "hints": ["Think from head to toe.", "What protects against noise, what against the chain, what against falling branches?", "One item combines three protective functions."]}, {"q": "Why is ear protection alone not enough with the plate compactor? What other PPE is needed?", "answer": "Besides <b>ear protection</b>, <b>safety boots S3</b> with a steel toe cap are essential, because the plate can land on your foot. In addition, <b>gloves</b> to counter the vibration and <b>safety goggles</b> or a <b>dust mask</b> when dust is stirred up.", "hints": ["Think of your feet.", "The plate often weighs over 100 kg."]}]}, "botanik": {"id": "botanik", "title": "Botanical Names", "intro": "Botanical names are not random strings — they describe the plant. Once you know the building blocks, you can work names out instead of cramming them.", "tutorial": [{"heading": "Latin building-block kit: recurring species names", "html": "<p>Many species names <b>describe the plant</b>. Once you know these ~30 building blocks, you can decode new botanical names yourself — even ones that never came up in class.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Building block</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><i>vulgaris / vulgare</i></td><td>common, ordinary</td><td>Ligustrum vulgare, Berberis vulgaris</td></tr><tr><td><i>sanguinea / -eus</i></td><td>blood-red</td><td>Cornus sanguinea (red winter twigs)</td></tr><tr><td><i>nigra / -um</i></td><td>black</td><td>Sambucus nigra (black berries)</td></tr><tr><td><i>alba / -um</i></td><td>white</td><td>Cornus alba, Symphoricarpos albus</td></tr><tr><td><i>rubra / -um</i></td><td>red</td><td>Quercus rubra (red oak)</td></tr><tr><td><i>lutea / -um</i></td><td>yellow</td><td>—</td></tr><tr><td><i>glauca / -um</i></td><td>blue-grey, with a waxy bloom</td><td>Festuca glauca, Picea pungens 'Glauca'</td></tr><tr><td><i>spinosa / -us</i></td><td>thorny, prickly (spina = thorn)</td><td>Prunus spinosa (blackthorn/sloe)</td></tr><tr><td><i>sempervirens</i></td><td>evergreen (semper = always + virens = greening)</td><td>Buxus sempervirens</td></tr><tr><td><i>baccata / -us</i></td><td>berry-bearing</td><td>Taxus baccata (yew)</td></tr><tr><td><i>aquifolium</i></td><td>pointed-/needle-leaved (acus = needle + folium = leaf)</td><td>Ilex aquifolium, Mahonia aquifolium</td></tr><tr><td><i>scoparius / -a</i></td><td>broom-like (scopa = broom)</td><td>Cytisus scoparius (common broom)</td></tr><tr><td><i>officinalis</i></td><td>medicinal, \"of the apothecary\"</td><td>Salvia officinalis</td></tr><tr><td><i>odorata / -um</i></td><td>fragrant, scented</td><td>—</td></tr><tr><td><i>canina / -us</i></td><td>of the dog</td><td>Rosa canina (dog rose)</td></tr><tr><td><i>mas</i></td><td>male</td><td>Cornus mas (cornelian cherry)</td></tr><tr><td><i>sylvatica / sylvestris</i></td><td>of the woods, woodland</td><td>Fagus sylvatica, Pinus sylvestris</td></tr><tr><td><i>montana / -us</i></td><td>of the mountains</td><td>—</td></tr><tr><td><i>palustris</i></td><td>growing in marshland, marsh-</td><td>Quercus palustris, Cirsium palustre</td></tr><tr><td><i>maritima / -us</i></td><td>coastal, of the sea</td><td>—</td></tr><tr><td><i>alpinum / -a</i></td><td>from the Alps, alpine</td><td>Ribes alpinum</td></tr><tr><td><i>europaeus / -a</i></td><td>European</td><td>Euonymus europaeus</td></tr><tr><td><i>japonica / sinensis / chinensis</i></td><td>Japanese / Chinese</td><td>Chaenomeles japonica, Wisteria sinensis</td></tr><tr><td><i>repens / reptans</i></td><td>creeping</td><td>Ajuga reptans (creeping bugle)</td></tr><tr><td><i>procumbens / prostrata</i></td><td>prostrate, creeping</td><td>Juniperus procumbens</td></tr><tr><td><i>pendula / -um</i></td><td>weeping, drooping</td><td>Betula pendula (silver/weeping birch)</td></tr><tr><td><i>fastigiata</i></td><td>columnar, stiffly upright</td><td>Carpinus betulus 'Fastigiata'</td></tr><tr><td><i>-oides</i></td><td>\"similar to …\"</td><td>rhamnoides = buckthorn-like</td></tr><tr><td><i>-folia / -folium</i></td><td>\"-leaved\"</td><td>aquifolium = pointed-leaved, sorbifolia = rowan-leaved</td></tr><tr><td><i>-flora / -florum</i></td><td>\"-flowered\"</td><td>grandiflora = large-flowered</td></tr></tbody></table><p><b>Note:</b> check the species name first for colour (alba, nigra, rubra, lutea, glauca, sanguinea), then for habitat (sylvatica, palustris, montana, alpinum, maritima), then for growth habit/leaf (repens, pendula, fastigiata, -folia) — that unlocks the majority of all names.</p>"}, {"heading": "The 17 wild-hedge names taken apart", "html": "<p>For each wild-hedge species, the meaning of the <b>genus</b> and <b>species name</b> — this is the most effective memory aid for working out the botanical name rather than cramming it by rote.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Botanical</th><th>Genus means</th><th>Species means</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><i>Rosa canina</i> (dog rose)</td><td><i>Rosa</i> = rose</td><td><i>canina</i> = \"of the dog\" (canis) — the \"common\" wild rose</td></tr><tr><td><i>Viburnum opulus</i> (guelder rose)</td><td><i>Viburnum</i> = old Latin name for rambling shrubs</td><td><i>opulus</i> = an old name, from the maple-like leaves</td></tr><tr><td><i>Viburnum lantana</i> (wayfaring tree)</td><td><i>Viburnum</i> = old Latin name for rambling shrubs</td><td><i>lantana</i> from \"lentus\" = pliant (pliant twigs)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Hippophae rhamnoides</i> (sea buckthorn)</td><td><i>Hippophae</i> = \"shining horse\" (Gk. hippos + phaos)</td><td><i>rhamnoides</i> = \"buckthorn-like\" (Rhamnus + -oides)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ligustrum vulgare</i> (privet)</td><td><i>Ligustrum</i> from \"ligare\" = to bind (rods for tying)</td><td><i>vulgare</i> = common, ordinary</td></tr><tr><td><i>Berberis vulgaris</i> (barberry)</td><td><i>Berberis</i> = from the Arabic name of the fruit</td><td><i>vulgaris</i> = common, ordinary</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus sanguinea</i> (common dogwood)</td><td><i>Cornus</i> = \"horn\" (cornu) — very hard wood</td><td><i>sanguinea</i> = blood-red — the red winter twigs</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus mas</i> (cornelian cherry)</td><td><i>Cornus</i> = \"horn\" (cornu) — very hard wood</td><td><i>mas</i> = \"male\" (vigorous, hard wood)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Prunus spinosa</i> (blackthorn/sloe)</td><td><i>Prunus</i> = plum/cherry</td><td><i>spinosa</i> = thorny, prickly (spina = thorn)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Sambucus nigra</i> (black elder)</td><td><i>Sambucus</i> from Gk. \"sambuke\" (an instrument — hollow stems)</td><td><i>nigra</i> = black — the black berries</td></tr><tr><td><i>Euonymus europaeus</i> (spindle)</td><td><i>Euonymus</i> = \"of good name\" (eu + onoma) — ironic, since poisonous</td><td><i>europaeus</i> = European</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cytisus scoparius</i> (common broom)</td><td><i>Cytisus</i> = old name for a clover-like shrub</td><td><i>scoparius</i> = broom-like (scopa = broom)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ilex aquifolium</i> (holly)</td><td><i>Ilex</i> = Latin name for the holm oak (similar foliage)</td><td><i>aquifolium</i> = pointed-/needle-leaved (acus + folium)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Buxus sempervirens</i> (box)</td><td><i>Buxus</i> from Gk. \"pyxos\" (box tree)</td><td><i>sempervirens</i> = evergreen (semper + virens)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ribes alpinum</i> (alpine currant)</td><td><i>Ribes</i> from Arabic/Persian \"ribas\" = sour</td><td><i>alpinum</i> = from the Alps, alpine</td></tr><tr><td><i>Corylus avellana</i> (hazel)</td><td><i>Corylus</i> from Gk. \"korys\" = helmet (the fruit husk)</td><td><i>avellana</i> = \"from Avella\" (an Italian town famed for hazelnuts)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Syringa vulgaris</i> (common lilac)</td><td><i>Syringa</i> from Gk. \"syrinx\" = reed/pipe (hollow twigs)</td><td><i>vulgaris</i> = common, ordinary</td></tr></tbody></table>"}, {"heading": "Identifying by leaf arrangement and leaf shape", "html": "<p><b>First move in any woody-plant identification: the leaf arrangement.</b> Are the leaves set <b>in opposite pairs</b> (opposite) or <b>singly and staggered</b> (alternate)? This one question immediately halves the shortlist — it is the fastest identifying feature there is.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Species</th><th>Leaf arrangement</th><th>Leaf shape</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><i>Viburnum opulus</i> — guelder rose</td><td>opposite</td><td>3–5-lobed, maple-like</td></tr><tr><td><i>Viburnum lantana</i> — wayfaring tree</td><td>opposite</td><td>simple, egg-shaped, <b>wrinkled</b>, felted underneath (\"woolly\")</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ligustrum vulgare</i> — privet</td><td>opposite</td><td>simple, lance-shaped, entire margin; semi-evergreen</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus sanguinea</i> — common dogwood</td><td>opposite</td><td>simple, egg-shaped, with arching veins</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus mas</i> — cornelian cherry</td><td>opposite</td><td>simple, egg-shaped, with arching veins</td></tr><tr><td><i>Sambucus nigra</i> — black elder</td><td>opposite</td><td>odd-pinnate, 5–7 serrated leaflets</td></tr><tr><td><i>Euonymus europaeus</i> — spindle</td><td>opposite; shoots green and <b>four-angled</b></td><td>simple, elliptical, finely serrated</td></tr><tr><td><i>Buxus sempervirens</i> — box</td><td>opposite</td><td>small, leathery, entire margin, evergreen</td></tr><tr><td><i>Syringa vulgaris</i> — common lilac</td><td>opposite</td><td>simple, heart-shaped, entire margin</td></tr><tr><td><i>Rosa canina</i> — dog rose</td><td>alternate</td><td>odd-pinnate, 5–7 serrated leaflets</td></tr><tr><td><i>Hippophae rhamnoides</i> — sea buckthorn</td><td>alternate</td><td>narrow lance-shaped, silvery-scaly</td></tr><tr><td><i>Berberis vulgaris</i> — barberry</td><td>alternate, clustered on short shoots; plus thorns</td><td>simple, obovate, finely spiny-toothed</td></tr><tr><td><i>Prunus spinosa</i> — blackthorn/sloe</td><td>alternate</td><td>simple, small, serrated</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ilex aquifolium</i> — holly</td><td>alternate; evergreen</td><td>leathery, wavy and spiny-toothed — <b>upper leaves often smooth-margined</b></td></tr><tr><td><i>Ribes alpinum</i> — alpine currant</td><td>alternate</td><td>small, 3–5-lobed (typical of currants)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Corylus avellana</i> — hazel</td><td>alternate</td><td>simple, roundish, doubly serrated, shortly pointed</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cytisus scoparius</i> — common broom</td><td>leaves small/trifoliate, often greatly reduced</td><td>green rod-like shoots — appears almost leafless</td></tr></tbody></table><p><b>Learn the opposite-leaved ones as a group:</b> both Viburnum species, both dogwoods, privet, elder, spindle, box and lilac. Everything else in the wild hedge is alternate.</p>"}, {"heading": "Meaning of genus names and species epithets", "html": "<p>The <b>Plant knowledge</b> topic so far only explains the <i>structure</i> of the botanical name (genus/species/cultivar). What's missing is the strongest memory aid of all: <b>what the Latin words mean</b>. Once you know that <i>sanguinea</i> means \"blood-red\", you'll never forget Cornus sanguinea, the common dogwood, again. To be added as a new cheat-sheet section in <code>topics.js</code> → <code>pflanzenkenntnisse</code>:</p><p><b>heading:</b> \"Latin building-block kit: what the botanical names mean\"</p><p><b>html:</b></p><p>Almost every botanical name describes the plant. The <b>genus name</b> is usually an old Latin or Greek name, while the <b>species epithet</b> names a feature, the habitat or the origin. Once you know the building blocks, you don't have to memorise the names — you can work them out.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Botanical name</th><th>Genus means</th><th>Species name means</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><i>Acer campestre</i><br>field maple</td><td><i>Acer</i> = maple (sharp/pointed)</td><td><i>campestre</i> = of the field</td></tr><tr><td><i>Berberis vulgaris</i><br>barberry</td><td><i>Berberis</i> = Arabic name of the fruit</td><td><i>vulgaris</i> = common</td></tr><tr><td><i>Buxus sempervirens</i><br>box</td><td><i>Buxus</i> = Gk. pyxos</td><td><i>sempervirens</i> = evergreen (semper + virens)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Carpinus betulus</i><br>hornbeam</td><td><i>Carpinus</i> = Latin name</td><td><i>betulus</i> = birch-like</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus mas</i><br>cornelian cherry</td><td><i>Cornus</i> = horn (hard wood)</td><td><i>mas</i> = male</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cornus sanguinea</i><br>common dogwood</td><td><i>Cornus</i> = horn (hard wood)</td><td><i>sanguinea</i> = blood-red (red twigs)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Corylus avellana</i><br>hazel</td><td><i>Corylus</i> = Gk. korys = helmet</td><td><i>avellana</i> = from Avella (hazelnut)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Cytisus scoparius</i><br>common broom</td><td><i>Cytisus</i> = old name (clover-like)</td><td><i>scoparius</i> = broom-like (scopa = broom)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Euonymus europaeus</i><br>spindle</td><td><i>Euonymus</i> = \"of good name\" (ironic: poisonous)</td><td><i>europaeus</i> = European</td></tr><tr><td><i>Fagus sylvatica</i><br>European beech</td><td><i>Fagus</i> = Latin name of the beech</td><td><i>sylvatica</i> = of the woods</td></tr><tr><td><i>Hippophae rhamnoides</i><br>sea buckthorn</td><td><i>Hippophae</i> = \"shining horse\"</td><td><i>rhamnoides</i> = buckthorn-like</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ilex aquifolium</i><br>holly</td><td><i>Ilex</i> = name of the holm oak</td><td><i>aquifolium</i> = pointed-leaved (acus + folium)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ligustrum vulgare</i><br>privet</td><td><i>Ligustrum</i> = from ligare = to bind</td><td><i>vulgare</i> = common</td></tr><tr><td><i>Prunus spinosa</i><br>blackthorn/sloe</td><td><i>Prunus</i> = plum/cherry</td><td><i>spinosa</i> = thorny (spina = thorn)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Ribes alpinum</i><br>alpine currant</td><td><i>Ribes</i> = Arabic/Persian ribas (sour)</td><td><i>alpinum</i> = from the Alps</td></tr><tr><td><i>Rosa canina</i><br>dog rose</td><td><i>Rosa</i> = rose</td><td><i>canina</i> = of the dog (canis)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Sambucus nigra</i><br>black elder</td><td><i>Sambucus</i> = Gk. instrument (hollow stems)</td><td><i>nigra</i> = black</td></tr><tr><td><i>Syringa vulgaris</i><br>common lilac</td><td><i>Syringa</i> = Gk. syrinx = pipe</td><td><i>vulgaris</i> = common</td></tr><tr><td><i>Taxus baccata</i><br>European yew</td><td><i>Taxus</i> = Latin name of the yew</td><td><i>baccata</i> = berry-bearing (bacca = berry)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Viburnum lantana</i><br>wayfaring tree</td><td><i>Viburnum</i> = old Latin name</td><td><i>lantana</i> = pliant (lentus)</td></tr><tr><td><i>Viburnum opulus</i><br>guelder rose</td><td><i>Viburnum</i> = old Latin name</td><td><i>opulus</i> = maple-like (old name)</td></tr></tbody></table><p><b>The most common building blocks to recognise:</b> <i>vulgaris/vulgare</i> = common · <i>sylvatica</i> = of the woods · <i>campestre</i> = of the field · <i>alpinum</i> = of the Alps · <i>nigra</i> = black · <i>sanguinea</i> = blood-red · <i>spinosa</i> = thorny · <i>sempervirens</i> = evergreen · <i>-folium</i> = leaf · <i>-oides</i> = similar to.</p>"}], "exam": [{"q": "What do the species names sempervirens, vulgaris and sanguinea mean? Give one example of each.", "answer": "<b>sempervirens</b> = evergreen (<i>Buxus sempervirens</i>, box). <b>vulgaris</b> = common, widespread (<i>Ligustrum vulgare</i>, privet; <i>Berberis vulgaris</i>, barberry). <b>sanguinea</b> = blood-red (<i>Cornus sanguinea</i>, common dogwood — after its red winter twigs).", "hints": ["semper = always.", "vulgaris crops up in very many native species.", "sanguis is the Latin word for blood."]}, {"q": "You are standing in front of an unknown woody plant. Which question do you ask first, and why?", "answer": "First the <b>leaf arrangement</b>: are the leaves <b>opposite</b> (set in pairs facing each other) or <b>alternate</b> (single and staggered)? This is the fastest identifying feature, because it immediately roughly halves the species in question. Only then come leaf shape, margin, fruit and bark.", "hints": ["It's not about the flower.", "The answer immediately halves the shortlist."]}]}};
